====Usage notes====
果 follows the grammatical rules of its Middle Korean descendant, which differ from Modern Korean usage. Thus it may be followed by other case markers, such as {{m|oko|叱}}. Furthermore, in both Old and Middle Korean, "A and B" is expressed as A-''kwa'' B-''kwa'', instead of Modern Korean A-''kwa'' B.

Unlike in Middle and Modern Korean, 果 did not take any allomorph following a vowel. The Middle Korean allomorph {{okm-inline|와|-Gwa}} was produced by the lenition of Old Korean *k to /ɣ/ between vowels.

